<LP>
   Gannett Co.'s first foray into the sale of cross-media
packages -- offering advertisers the chance to tap
simultaneously into its vast newspaper, television, radio and
billboard properties -- was a colossal failure in 1984.
   But now, five years after Gannett pulled the plug on the
plan, the media giant is gearing up to make another run at
the business. It has set up a task force to study the idea
and says it wants to have "a few" advertisers try the
cross-media program in 1991.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "It was really an idea before its time," says Cathleen
Black, publisher of USA Today and executive vice president of
marketing at Gannett. "But we've had some internal
discussions, and we think it's time again to rethink this."
   But Gannett's idea isn't unique anymore, and it may find
that the market is already glutted with media companies that
have recently gotten into the cross-media ad package
business. Earlier this week, Washington Post Co.'s Newsweek
and Times Mirror Corp. announced a multimedia ad package.
Time Warner Inc., with its diverse interests from publishing
to cable TV, is also testing the waters, as is Hearst Corp.,
which owns magazines and the Lifetime cable network. Meredith
Corp. offers cross-media ad deals, too.
   Gannett, though, says its programs will be different
because its regional media outlets would allow advertisers to
target their messages at very narrow local segments.
Advertisers that sign up could tap its 10 TV stations, 15
radio stations, 83 newspapers, USA Today and its outdoor
billboard network. Ms. Black says the company might even link
with non-Gannett media, such as a magazine or in-store media,
if an advertiser wanted that.
   Still, some ad agency media directors aren't sure how big
a market there is for such deals. They warn that the programs
may appeal only to a very small group of big-spending
advertisers. And there are other concerns: "Media companies
have difficulty because they don't understand the needs of
the clients," says John Belfiore, senior vice president of
media planning services at ad agency BBDO.
   Gannett acknowledges that it stumbled the first time
because it forced advertisers to select from rigid ad
packages that Gannett itself created. One package, for
example, might have offered billboard and radio ads -- but
not TV. Now Gannett is demonstrating a flexibility common to
more and more media companies these days. Programs now will
be created one-on-one with advertisers, Gannett says.
   Ms. Black says Gannett decided to give the program a
second try in part because of interest from advertisers,
which said their marketing departments were facing cuts. The
advertisers, she says, were looking to Gannett and other
media companies not just for ad pages, but for marketing
advice.
   "We do know that the easier you make it for them, the
better your chance of selling a program," Ms. Black says. "In
this day and age, the closer you are to your customer's
thinking, the better off you will be in creating ideas and
programs that match their objectives."
   While Ms. Black touts the benefits of such packages, she
warns that advertisers who sign up won't get the big volume
discount some other programs offer. The program was primarily
developed, she says, to "get incremental dollars for
Gannett."
   Although they're taking a wait-and-see approach, some
media directors at ad agencies say corporate advertisers,
particulary the big spenders, might be interested in looking
into the packages if media companies can convince them that
they have the know-how to offer individualized, tailored
service.
   "The kinds of group deals or buys that were offered in the
past weren't flexible enough, and as a result, there wasn't
much business that grew out of them," says Rich Hamilton,
senior vice president at D'Arcy Masius Benton &amp; Bowles. "The
media companies are recognizing the need to be more flexibile
. . . and that's a positive thing," he says.
