   Alaska Launches Ad Blitz
                                                                                                       

   Do you think Alaska's shoreline is still awash in oil? The
Alaska Visitors Association, using $7 million from Exxon, is
mounting a TV ad blitz to convince you otherwise.
   The 30-second spots, which will run about 60 times a week
for four weeks, broke yesterday in 35 major markets. Each of
the three spots features new footage of Prince William Sound
-- and its mammal and marine life -- with no visible effects
from the Exxon Valdez spill last year. A typical line: "The
sapphire of Prince William Sound nearly recovered from the
spill."
   "Our research showed there is a substantial misperception
about the effects of the spill," says Robert Dindinger,
president of the 600-member trade association. "Nobody is
going to come to Alaska and see dead animals on the beach."
   Mr. Dindinger said the number of tourists visiting Alaska
has actually risen slightly since the spill. But that growth,
at an annual rate of 2% to 3%, is a far cry from the
double-digit growth the state had seen in the 1980s.
   Exxon, whose funding was termed voluntary by both parties,
shared creative control of the commercials. The oil company
"will benefit by dispelling misperceptions about conditions
in Prince William Sound," an Exxon spokesman said.
